        {
            "beta_headline": null,
            "category": "crypto",
            "date": "2025-04-02",
            "headline": "Fidelity now offers IRAs for crypto investing with minimal fees. No fees to open or maintain accounts, but 1% spread on buy/sell transactions. US crypto landscape evolving. Some IRA providers allowed crypto purchases; Fidelity's move indicates a shift. Options like BTC and ETH ETFs available since 2024. Rise of Bitcoin IRAs and companies like BitIRA catering to digital assets. Momentum in allowing crypto in retirement accounts seen with a bill by Alabama Senator Tuberville.",
            "id": "9f266f0c-0b39-4bf3-bad8-64f492358b68",
            "is_major": false,
            "source": "Cointelegraph",
            "source_type": "news",
            "summary": "Fidelity, a financial services company managing $5.9 trillion in assets, has launched new retirement accounts allowing Americans to invest in crypto fee-free. These include a tax-deferred traditional IRA and two Roth IRAs, with the option to buy Bitcoin, Ether, and Litecoin. Fidelity charges a 1% spread on crypto transactions, making the process easier for individuals. The majority of crypto holdings are kept in cold storage for security. Previously, few IRA providers permitted cryptocurrency purchases, indicating a shift in the landscape. Since 2024, ETFs have offered exposure to BTC and ETH in retirement accounts. The growing trend of including crypto in retirement accounts is evident, with Senator Tuberville reintroducing a bill to allow crypto in 401(k)s.",
            "tickers": [],
            "time": "21:46:37",
